<center>
<h1>
Models of Categorization
</h1>
<h2>
<a href="http://www.indiana.edu/~kruschke/home.html>John K. Kruschke</a><br>
Outline of Guest Lecture for Q500, 27 September 1995<br>
</h2>
<pre>http://www.indiana.edu/~jkkteach/Q500/categorization.html</pre>
</center>

<ol>

<p><strong><li>Goals of Cognitive Science:</strong>

<ul>

<p><li>Explanation at both functional (software) and implementational
(hardware) levels.

<p><li>Explanatory principles and formalization.  

<ul> <li>Structure of modeling. <li>Formalization yields precision,
explicitness, and theorist-independent predictions. <li>Why do we all
know the legend that an apple fell on Isaac Newton's head? <br>(A: Not
because of the explanatory principle, but because of the
formalization.) </ul>

<p><li>Caveat: <em>Shun ontological reification!</em>  <br>E.g., gravity.
Representations and processes are in the models, not necessarily in
the mind/brain.

</ul>

<p><strong><li>Overview of <a
href="http://www.indiana.edu/~kruschke/home.html#research>My
Research:</a></strong>

<ul>

<p><li>Categorization. 

<ul> <li>The laboratory learning paradigm. <li>Types of empirical
phenomena.  </ul>

<p><li>Explanatory Principles.

<ul> <li>Two-pronged approach: 1. Empirical testing. 2. Modeling.
Logic is the same for both. <li>
<a href="http://www.indiana.edu/~kruschke/fiveprinc_abstract.html">
Some specific principles</a>. </ul>

</ul>

<p><strong><li>Principle of Selective Attention to Relevant Dimensions.</strong>

<ul> <p><li>Empirical phenomenon: 
<a href="http://www.indiana.edu/~kruschke/filcon_abstract.html">
Filtration vs. Condensation</a>.

<p><li>Formalization: <a
href="http://www.indiana.edu/~kruschke/alcove_abstract.html"> ALCOVE
</a> (cf. vanilla backprop). </ul>

<p><strong><li>Principle of Rapidly Shifting Selective Attention.</strong>

<ul> <p><li>Empirical phenomenon: 
<a href="http://www.indiana.edu/~kruschke/baserate_abstract.html">
Inverse base rate effect.</a>
<p><li>Formalization: 
<a href="http://www.indiana.edu/~kruschke/baserate_abstract.html">
ADIT</a> (cf. vanilla linear associator). </ul>

</ol>

<p>
